THE YEARBOOKS ARE IN!!!

THE 2020 YEARBOOK PICKUP will be this Tuesday, September 15h, from 3 PM - 7 PM outside of the Auditorium & Main Gym. Aside from picking up your yearbook, class points toward the SPIRIT STICK 2021 will be awarded to the current class that has the most students come & pick up their pre-paid yearbooks, along with incentives for the first class to 25 pickups, 50 pickups, 100 pickups, etc.

As usual, these precautionary steps must be taken when on campus to pick up your yearbook:
1. Masks must be worn
2. Social Distancing will be a priority
3. STAY HOME if you are sick (email ksullivan@d220.org asking for an additional time for pickup).

We look forward to seeing everyone on Tuesday!
As always, GO RAMS!

post_text: This week's Rams Are Responsible Winners are Jasmine Karim and Belal Almahbosh. Mrs. Shewmaker nominated Belal Almahbosh and said, "Belal has done an awesome job with his e-learning assignments! Switching from classroom learning to e-learning has not changed Belal's commitment to doing his best. Belal is always the first to join and last to leave our weekly zoom meetings. He is actively engaged in weekly assignments and emailing me when he needs help. I am going to miss the positive affect he gives in the classroom next year." Jasmine was nominated by Mrs. Kadas who stated, "Jasmine is always a dedicated student. During e-learning, she has continued to put forth a great deal of effort intro every project. Our final art project asked students to create pandemic masks that reflect their emotions about our current situation. Jasmine created an original, thoughtful, and impressive art piece." Congratulations!

post_text:
Dr. Riordan began an initiative at the start of April to show our appreciation and admiration for all of the people working at local hospitals—and support our local restaurants at the same time.

He asked that every staff member consider donating any amount of money they could afford to a special account called the “Reavis Rapid Response Fund.” The money raised would go towards gift cards from Burbank restaurants and food establishments. These gift cards/certificates were delivered to our local hospitals: Christ Medical Center, Palos Community Hospital, and Little Company of Mary Hospital. The initial goal of $7000 was surpassed in days, and, after a two week donation period, the Reavis Staff generously gave over $12,000 to the effort!

Thank you to our front-line hospital workers! Thank you to our local businesses for feeding our community. And thank you to Dr. Riordan and the Reavis staff for their generosity. We are all truly Better Together!💙🐏💙

post_text:
Congratulations to our Weronika Orawiec and Gaby Kuhar on being named this week's Rams Are Responsible Winners.

Weronika was nominated by Mrs. Mathisen who stated, "Weronika has taken ownership of each weekly learning module during our distance learning. She has remained diligent in her studies and completing all her assignments. Weronika also extended help in the classroom setting prior to our remote learning period. It is evident that this student values learning and continues the learning process outside of the classroom."

Mr. LaMantia nominated Gaby and said, "Gaby took the time to write a letter to teachers and staff for everything they are doing during eLearning. She also sent letters to the Burbank police , fire departments and the local stores. She decorated her front lawn, all the windows, and even the brick of her front porch with hearts and positive messages in construction paper and chalk for our neighbors. Gaby wants to be a part of her community and make sure everyone knows they are not alone in this and neither is she."

Congratulations Weronika and Gaby!!!

post_text:
Industrial Tech teacher Mr. Jones is volunteering his time and using his 3-D printing knowledge to help others during this crisis.
Mr. Jones converted his basement into a 3-D printing lab. With the help of his wife and kids, he has currently made over 500 personal protection equipment items for frontline medical workers and first responders.
Face shields, ear savers, and bias tape makers have already been donated to local hospitals and mask makers. Today Mr. Jones made a special PPE delivery, (that included a Girl Scout cookie donation from a former Burbank resident) to the Burbank Fire Department.
Thank you Mr. Jones, and thank you to all medical workers and first responders for everything you do!

post_text: With 5 weeks until the SAT, our juniors have blown past the halfway point as they have accrued over 7.5 million points toward the Junior Class Challenge! They are splitting time between the Math and Evidence-Based Reading and Writing sections as they work on Khan Academy. Individualized SAT practice is always available any time they have an Internet connection, and some even squeeze extra time in while they’re on the go by accessing Khan on their phones! The juniors are certainly showing no signs of slowing down as we approach the final stretch! Keep up the great work, Junior Rams, and remember to BE THERE, BE FOCUSED, and BE DRIVEN!

The Reavis Speech Team placed 9th in the IHSA State Speech Tournament this weekend in Peoria!

Junior Oswaldo Ocampo was in the Final Round on Saturday in TWO events! He finished 3rd in the State of Illinois in Oratorical Declamation AND Dramatic Interpretation! A double-medalist is about as good as it gets -Congrats, Oswaldo!

post_text:
Congrats to our Scholastic Bowl Varsity Team for placing 2nd in the South Suburban Red Conference Tournament last night. In round one, the Rams gained a decisive victory over Richards, leading us to face the undefeated Oak Lawn for round two. Reavis took the lead early and held onto it for the entire match and the final score was 300 to 210. Unfortunately, the Rams fell to Argo in the final match by 40 points.

Reavis had two students earn all-conference medals for toss-ups. Varsity member Karol Turbiarz with 48 and JV player Gabriel Sanchez with 40.

Next up is Regionals at Sandburg March 9th.

Congrats to the entire team, Head Coach Jeff Mazzone, and assistant Sam Krueger. Best of luck in the IHSA series! Go Rams!!!

post_text:
PARENTS/GUARDIAN FEEDBACK NEEDED

Illinois 5Essentials Parent/Guardian Survey
Please access the link at:
https://survey.5-essentials.org/illinois/?target_name=parent.

The parent/guardian survey will take under 10 minutes to complete. You may skip questions you do not wish to answer, but the survey must be completed in one sitting and cannot be retrieved once it is submitted.

If you decide to take the survey, your identity will be kept completely confidential and your responses will not be linked to you. In addition, school-level reports will only be generated if at least 20 percent of our parents/guardians complete the survey, which can be accessed by visiting https://survey.5-essentials.org/illinois/.

The results will be made available to the public via the State School Report Cards, which will be released in the fall.

You can access general information about the Illinois 5Essentials Survey by visiting https://illinois.5-essentials.org/.

Thank you for participating in this important endeavor and for your continued support of our schools and the children we serve.

PARENTS AND GUARDIANS WE NEED YOUR FEEDBACK!!!

Illinois 5Essentials Parent/Guardian Survey
Please access the link at:
https://survey.5-essentials.org/illinois/?target_name=parent.

The parent/guardian survey will take under 10 minutes to complete. You may skip questions you do not wish to answer, but the survey must be completed in one sitting and cannot be retrieved once it is submitted.

If you decide to take the survey, your identity will be kept completely confidential and your responses will not be linked to you. In addition, school-level reports will only be generated if at least 20 percent of our parents/guardians complete the survey, which can be accessed by visiting https://survey.5-essentials.org/illinois/.

The results will be made available to the public via the State School Report Cards, which will be released in the fall.

You can access general information about the Illinois 5Essentials Survey by visiting https://illinois.5-essentials.org/.

Thank you for participating in this important endeavor and for your continued support of our schools and the children we serve.
